'''Francis Henry Bateman-Champain''' (17 June 1877 â€“ 29 December 1942) was an English [[cricket]]er playing primarily for [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]] and [[Oxford University cricket team]]s between 1895 and 1914.<ref name="cricpro">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/9596.html | title=Player Profile: Francis Bateman-Champain | publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> A right-handed batsman and occasional right-arm slow bowler, he came from a cricketing family: his brothers [[John Bateman-Champain|John]], [[Claude Bateman-Champain|Claude]] and [[Hugh Bateman-Champain|Hugh]] all played [[first-class cricket]]. His uncles Fendall, [[Sir Frederick Currie, 2nd Baronet|Frederick]], Robert and William Currie also played.<ref name="capro">{{cite web | url=https://cricketarchive.com/Players/27/27745/27745.html | title=Player Profile: Francis Bateman-Champain | publisher=Cricket Archive | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> Francis played 114 matches in his career, scoring 4,677 runs at a [[batting average (cricket)|batting average]] of 24.61. over 3,300 of these were scored for Gloucestershire, for whom he made four of his five centuries.<ref name="FC Statistics By Team - Batting">{{cite web | url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27745/f_Batting_by_Team.html | title=FC Statistics By Team - Batting | publisher=Cricket Archive | accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> Born in [[Richmond Hill, London|Richmond Hill]], [[Surrey]], he died in [[Tiverton, Devon|Tiverton]], [[Devon]].<ref name="cricpro" />

Bateman-Champaign was educated at [[Cheltenham College]] and [[Hertford College, Oxford]]. He became a schoolteacher and taught at [[Wellington College, Berkshire|Wellington College]] and at Cheltenham College.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mr F. H. B. Champaign |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=1 January 1943 |page=7}}</ref>

